chore: initialize repository
---
docs: add the Intrinsic Green's Learning manuscript

The seminal IGL paper (LaTeX). IGL models a target on a manifold as the solution of a
linear PDE whose source is learned from data and integrated against a Green's kernel; an
encoder discovers a chart on which source and kernel decompose, giving a finite separable
Master Formula with cost linear in the intrinsic dimension.

Cites: Quemy 2026, Intrinsic Green's Learning
---
conjecture(master-formula): the Green's integral factorises as a finite separable rank-K×R sum

Claim-ID: conjecture:master-formula
Status: math.conjectured
---
conjecture(naive-separable): a curved-chart Green's kernel factorises separably without metric compensation

On a curved chart the integral carries a metric volume factor √|g|. This conjectures the
kernel still factorises separably as-is, with no compensation: the naive position the
separability-barrier analysis later tests.

Claim-ID: conjecture:naive-separable
Status: math.conjectured
---
axiomatize~(green-kernel): posit the elliptic Green's kernel operator

Mathlib has no elliptic-PDE Green's-function theory, so the kernel G with u = G*f solving
Lu = f is posited per operator as a cited axiom rather than constructed.

Lean: IGL.greensKernel
Status: math.axiomatised
AXIOM: IGL.greensKernel (elliptic Green's kernel; posited per operator, absent from Mathlib)
---
axiomatize~(exp-sum): cite the logarithmic exponential-sum rank bound

The separable rank K needed to approximate an elliptic Green's kernel to accuracy ε is
O(log 1/ε), independent of dimension (Braess–Hackbusch exponential sums). Mathlib has no
exp-sum approximation theory, so it is posited as a cited axiom.

Lean: IGL.expSumRank_logBound
Status: math.axiomatised
AXIOM: IGL.expSumRank_logBound (separable rank K = O(log 1/ε), dimension-independent)
Cites: Braess & Hackbusch 2005, Numer. Math.
---
formalize(rank1): the rank-1 two-factor separable factorization

Lean: igl_separable_factorization
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound
Verified-By: Lean 4.30.0; Mathlib v4.30.0
---
formalize(master-formula): close the d-fold factorization and the Master Formula

A rank-R separable source and rank-K separable kernel collapse the d-dimensional Green's
integral to the finite sum ∑_{k,r} γ_k w_r ∏_j I_{k,r,j} via Fubini: the O(N^d) → O(KRd)
reduction.

Lean: IGL.separableSource, IGL.separableKernel, IGL.partialIntegral, IGL.iglParticular, IGL.fubini_dfold, IGL.fubini_factorization
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound
Verified-By: Lean 4.30.0; Mathlib v4.30.0
Depends-On: igl_separable_factorization
Closes: conjecture:master-formula
---
formalize(corollaries): the KAN and Additive-Green reductions and gauge invariance

K=1 gives the Additive-Green case; the identity-kernel limit gives the Kolmogorov–Arnold
form; and the prediction integral is invariant under any measure-preserving reparametrisation.

Lean: IGL.additiveGreen_factorization, IGL.kan_reduction, IGL.gauge_invariance
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound
Verified-By: Lean 4.30.0; Mathlib v4.30.0
Depends-On: IGL.fubini_factorization, IGL.fubini_dfold
---
formalize(spectral): the spectral factorized integral

The exponential-sum surrogate turns additive eigenvalue coupling into a product, after which
the multi-index mode sum factorizes across axes: the discrete analogue of the Master Formula.

Lean: IGL.exp_neg_sum_eigs, IGL.spectral_factorization
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound
Verified-By: Lean 4.30.0; Mathlib v4.30.0
---
formalize(cp-rank): CP-rank sub-additivity, sub-multiplicativity, and rank-friendly differentiation

A constructive CP-rank predicate with rank(f+g) ≤ rank f + rank g, rank(f·g) ≤ rank f · rank g,
and a separable operator mapping a rank-R source to rank ≤ R·d.

Lean: IGL.HasCPRank, IGL.separableSource_hasCPRank, IGL.HasCPRank.add, IGL.HasCPRank.mul, IGL.applyCoordOp_hasCPRank
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound
Verified-By: Lean 4.30.0; Mathlib v4.30.0
---
formalize(barrier-if): the separability barrier, sufficiency direction

If the metric factor is itself separable, √|g|(ζ)=∏_j χ_j(ζ_j), the compensated Green's
integral still factorizes into d one-dimensional integrals: the metric is absorbed
axis-by-axis and the barrier does not appear.

Lean: IGL.barrier_if_factorization
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound
Verified-By: Lean 4.30.0; Mathlib v4.30.0
Depends-On: IGL.fubini_dfold
---
formalize(barrier-onlyif): a degree-2 metric is not rank-1: the barrier's necessity witness

A machine-checked counterexample: the metric factor 1 + ζ₀ζ₁ on ℝ² is not rank-1 (not of
product form a(ζ₀)·b(ζ₁)). This is the rigorous core of the separability barrier's necessity
direction; the general converse needs genericity hypotheses and is left informal.

Lean: IGL.barrierWitness_not_rank_one
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound
Verified-By: Lean 4.30.0; Mathlib v4.30.0
Depends-On: IGL.HasCPRank
---
refute(naive-separable)!: the rank-1 counterexample blocks naive separable factorization

The machine-checked witness IGL.barrierWitness_not_rank_one exhibits a metric factor that is
not rank-1, so a single separable kernel cannot absorb it. The naive-separable conjecture is
therefore false: curved-chart factorization requires metric compensation.

Status: math.disproved
Disproves: conjecture:naive-separable
Cites: IGL.barrierWitness_not_rank_one
BREAKING CHANGE: conjecture:naive-separable is withdrawn; curved-chart factorization needs metric compensation.
